# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antenna-arrays
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] An **adaptive beamformer** is a system that performs adaptive spatial signal processing with an array of transmitters or receivers.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] The signals are combined in a manner which increases the signal strength to/from a chosen direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Signals to/from other directions are combined in a benign or destructive manner, resulting in degradation of the signal to/from the undesired direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] This technique is used in both radio frequency and acoustic arrays, and provides for directional sensitivity without physically moving an array of receivers or transmitters.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Adaptive beamforming was initially developed in the 1960s for the military applications of sonar and radar.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] There exist several modern applications for beamforming, one of the most visible applications being commercial wireless networks such as LTE.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Initial applications of adaptive beamforming were largely focused in radar and electronic countermeasures to mitigate the effect of signal jamming in the military domain.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] An adaptive beamforming system relies on principles of wave propagation and phase relationships.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] See Constructive interference, and Beamforming.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Using the principles of superimposing waves, a higher or lower amplitude wave is created (e.g. by delaying and weighting the signal received).
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] The adaptive beamforming system dynamically adapts in order to maximize or minimize a desired parameter, such as Signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] There are several ways to approach the beamforming design, the first approach was implemented by maximizing the signal to noise ratio (SNR) by Applebaum 1965.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] This technique adapts the system parameters in order to maximize the receive signal power, while minimizing noise (such as interference or jamming).
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Another approach is the Least Mean Squares (LMS) error method implemented by Widrow, and Maximum Likelihood Method (MLM), developed in 1969 by Capon.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] Both the Applebaum and the Widrow algorithms are very similar, and converge toward an optimal solution.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] However, these techniques have implementation drawbacks.
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] In 1974, Reed demonstrated a technique known as Sample-Matrix Inversion (SMI).
[src:antenna-arrays/adaptive-beamformer] SMI determines the adaptive antenna array weights directly, unlike the algorithms of Applebaum and Widrow.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] An **antenna array** (or **array antenna**) is a set of multiple connected antennas which work together as a single antenna, to transmit or receive radio waves.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The individual antennas (called *elements*) are usually connected to a single receiver or transmitter by feedlines that feed the power to the elements in a specific phase relationship.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The radio waves radiated by each individual antenna combine and superpose, adding together (interfering constructively) to enhance the power radiated in desired directions, and cancelling (interfering destructively) to reduce the power radiated in other directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Similarly, when used for receiving, the separate radio frequency currents from the individual antennas combine in the receiver with the correct phase relationship to enhance signals received from the desired directions and cancel signals from undesired directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] More sophisticated array antennas may have multiple transmitter or receiver modules, each connected to a separate antenna element or group of elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] An antenna array can achieve higher gain (directivity), that is a narrower beam of radio waves, than could be achieved by a single element.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In general, the larger the number of individual antenna elements used, the higher the gain and the narrower the beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Some antenna arrays (such as military phased array radars) are composed of thousands of individual antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Arrays can be used to achieve higher gain, to give path diversity (also called MIMO) which increases communication reliability, to cancel interference from specific directions, to steer the radio beam electronically to point in different directions, and for radio direction finding (RDF).
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The term antenna array most commonly means a *driven array* consisting of multiple identical driven elements all connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] A *parasitic array* consists of a single driven element connected to the feedline, and other elements which are not, called parasitic elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] It is usually another name for a Yagi–Uda antenna.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] A *phased array* usually means an *electronically scanned array*; a driven array antenna in which each individual element is connected to the transmitter or receiver through a phase shifter controlled by a computer.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The beam of radio waves can be steered electronically to point instantly in any direction over a wide angle, without moving the antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] However the term "phased array" is sometimes used to mean an ordinary array antenna.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] From the Rayleigh criterion, the directivity of an antenna, the angular width of the beam of radio waves it emits, is proportional to the wavelength of the radio waves divided by the width of the antenna.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Small antennas around one wavelength in size, such as quarter-wave monopoles and half-wave dipoles, don't have much directivity (gain); they are omnidirectional antennas which radiate radio waves over a wide angle.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] One technique is to use reflection by large metal surfaces such as parabolic reflectors or horns, or refraction by dielectric lenses to change the direction of the radio waves, to focus the radio waves from a single low gain antenna into a beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] This type is called an *aperture antenna*.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] A parabolic dish is an example of this type of antenna.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] A second technique is to use multiple antennas which are fed from the same transmitter or receiver; this is called an array antenna, or antenna array.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] For a transmitting antenna the electromagnetic wave received at any point is the vector sum of the electromagnetic waves from each of the antenna elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] If the currents are fed to the antennas with the proper phase, due to the phenomenon of interference the spherical waves from the individual antennas combine (superpose) in front of the array to create plane waves, a beam of radio waves traveling in a specific direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In directions in which the waves from the individual antennas arrive in phase, the waves add together (constructive interference) to enhance the power radiated.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In directions in which the individual waves arrive out of phase, with the peak of one wave coinciding with the valley of another, the waves cancel (destructive interference) reducing the power radiated in that direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The radiation pattern of such an antenna consists of a strong beam in one direction, the main lobe, plus a series of weaker beams at different angles called sidelobes, usually representing residual radiation in unwanted directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The larger the width of the antenna and the greater the number of component antenna elements, the narrower the main lobe, and the higher the gain which can be achieved, and the smaller the sidelobes will be.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Arrays in which the antenna elements are fed in phase are broadside arrays; the main lobe is emitted perpendicular to the plane of the elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The largest array antennas are radio interferometers used in the field of radio astronomy, in which multiple radio telescopes consisting of large parabolic antennas are linked together into an antenna array, to achieve higher resolution.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Using the technique called aperture synthesis such an array can have the resolution of an antenna with a diameter equal to the distance between the antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In the technique called Very Long Baseline Interferometry (VLBI) dishes on separate continents have been linked, creating "array antennas" thousands of miles in size.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Most array antennas can be divided into two classes based on how the component antennas' axis relates to the radiation direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] There are also arrays (such as phased arrays) which don't belong to either of these categories, in which the direction of radiation is at some other angle to the antenna axis.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Let us consider a linear array whose elements are arranged along the x-axis of an orthogonal Cartesian reference system.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] It is assumed that radiators have the same spatial orientation and the same polarization for the electric field.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] where N is the number of antenna elements, k is the wavenumber, $I_{n}$ and $x_{n}$ (in meters) are the complex excitation coefficient and the position of the n-th radiator, respectively, ⁠ $u=\sin \theta \cos \phi$ ⁠, with $\theta$ and $\phi$ being the zenith angle and azimuth angle, respectively.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] If the spacing between adjacent elements is constant, then it can be written that ⁠ $x_{n+1}-x_{n}=d$ ⁠, and the array is said to be periodic.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The array is periodic both spatially (physically) and in the variable ⁠ u ⁠.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] For example, if ⁠ $d=\lambda /2$ ⁠, with $\lambda$ being the wavelength, then the magnitude of the array factor has a period, in the domain of ⁠ u ⁠, equal to 2.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] It is worth emphasising that u is an auxiliary variable.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In fact, from a physical point of view, the values of u that are of interest for radiative purposes fall in the interval [−1, 1], which is associated with the values of $\theta$ and ⁠ $\phi$ ⁠.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In this case, the interval [−1, 1] is called *visible space*.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] As shown further, if the definition of the variable u changes, the extent of the visible space also changes accordingly.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Now, suppose that the excitation coefficients are positive real variables.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In this case, always in the domain of ⁠ u ⁠, the array factor magnitude has a main lobe with maximum value at ⁠ $u=0$ ⁠, called *mainlobe*, several secondary lobes lower than the mainlobe, called *sidelobes* and mainlobe replicas called *grating-lobes*.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Grating lobes are a source of disadvantages in both transmission and reception.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Therefore, in periodic arrays, the spacing between adjacent radiators must not exceed a specific value to prevent the appearance of grating lobes *in the visible space*), the spacing between adjacent radiators must not exceed a specific value.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] For example, as seen previously, the first grating lobes for $d=\lambda /2$ occur in ⁠ $u=\pm 2$ ⁠.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] So, in this case, there are no problems since, in this way, the grating lobes are outside the interval [−1, 1].
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] As seen above, when the spacing is constant between adjacent radiators, the array factor is characterized by the presence of grating lobes.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In the literature, it has been amply demonstrated that to destroy the array factor's periodicity, the same array's geometry must also be made aperiodic.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] It is possible to act on the positions of the radiators so that these positions are *not commensurable* with each other.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Several methods have been developed to synthesize arrays in which also the positions represent further degrees of freedom (unknowns).
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] There are both deterministic and probabilistic methodologies.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Since the probabilistic theory of aperiodic arrays is a sufficiently systematised theory, with a strong general methodological basis, let us first concentrate on describing its peculiarities.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Suppose that the radiators positions, ⁠ $\{x_{n}\}_{n=1}^{N}$ ⁠, are independent and identically distributed random variables whose support coincides with the whole array aperture.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] In an antenna array providing a fixed radiation pattern, we may consider that the feed network is a part of the antenna array.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Thus, the antenna array has a single port.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Narrow beams can be formed, provided the phasing of each element of the array is appropriate.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] If, in addition, the amplitude of the excitation received by each element (during emission) is also well chosen, it is possible to synthesize a single-port array having a radiation pattern that closely approximates a specified pattern.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Many methods have been developed for array pattern synthesis.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Additional issues to be considered are matching, radiation efficiency and bandwidth.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] The design of an electronically steerable antenna array is different, because the phasing of each element can be varied, and possibly also the relative amplitude for each element.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Here, the antenna array has multiple ports, so that the subject matters of matching and efficiency are more involved than in the single-port case.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Moreover, matching and efficiency depend on the excitation, except when the interactions between the antennas can be ignored.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] An antenna array used for spatial diversity and/or spatial multiplexing (which are different types of MIMO radio communication) always has multiple ports.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] It is intended to receive independent excitations during emission, and to deliver more or less independent signals during reception.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Here also, the subject matters of matching and efficiency are involved, especially in the case of an antenna array of a mobile device, since, in this case, the surroundings of the antenna array influence its behavior, and vary over time.
[src:antenna-arrays/antenna-array] Suitable matching metrics and efficiency metrics take into account the worst possible excitations.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] In array antenna systems, **array gain** is the measure of the improvement in signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) achieved by the array.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] It is calculated as the SNR of the array output signal divided by the SNR of the array input signal.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] Intuitively, the array gain is realized by the fact that the signal is coherently added from *N* array elements, while the noise is incoherently added from those same elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] For a uniformly weighted array (un-tapered such that all elements contribute equally), the array gain is equal to *N*.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] Array gain is not the same thing as "gain," "power gain," "directive gain," or "directivity," but if the noise environment around the array is isotropic and the array input signal is from an isotropic radiator, then array gain is equal to gain defined in the usual way from the array beam pattern.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] The terms "power gain" and "directive gain" are deprecated by IEEE.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] In radio astronomy it is difficult to achieve a good signal-to-noise ratio because of background noise from modern communications.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] Even for strong astronomical radio emission it is typical for SNR levels to be below 0 decibels.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] To counter this problem exposure of the antenna to the source over large periods of time are needed just as in visible sky viewing.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] Array gain is achieved using multiple, even dozens of radio receivers to collect as much signal as possible.
[src:antenna-arrays/array-gain] Robots equipped with antenna arrays have better communication using array gain to eradicate dead spots and reduce interferences.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:antenna-arrays/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] For discrete aperture antennas (such as phased arrays) in which the element spacing is greater than a half wavelength, a spatial aliasing effect allows plane waves incident to the array from visible angles other than the desired direction to be coherently added, causing **grating lobes**.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Grating lobes are undesirable and identical to the main lobe.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The perceived difference seen in the grating lobes is because of the radiation pattern of non-isotropic antenna elements, which affects main and grating lobes differently.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] For isotropic antenna elements, the main and grating lobes are identical.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] To illustrate the concept of grating lobes, we will use a simple uniform linear array.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The beam pattern (or array factor) of any array can be defined as the dot product of the steering vector and the array manifold vector.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The ${\frac {N-1}{2}}$ term merely centers the point of reference for phase to the physical center of the array.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] From simple geometry, $\psi$ can be shown to be $\psi ={\frac {2\pi }{\lambda }}d\times \cos \theta$ , where $\theta$ is defined as the plane wave incident angle where $\theta =90^{\circ }$ is a plane wave incident orthogonal to the array (from boresight).
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] For a uniformly weighted (un-tapered) uniform linear array, the steering vector is of similar form to the manifold vector, but is "steered" to a target phase, $\psi _{T}$ , that may differ from the actual phase, $\psi$ of the impinging signal.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The resulting normalized array factor is a function of the phase difference, $\psi _{\Delta }=\psi -\psi _{T}$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The array factor is therefore periodic and maximized whenever the numerator and denominator both equal zero, by L'Hôpital's rule.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Thus, a maximum of unity is obtained for all integers n , where $\psi _{\Delta }=2\pi n$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Returning to our definition of $\theta$ , we wish to be able to steer the array electronically over the entire visible region, which extends from $\theta =0^{\circ }$ to $\theta =180^{\circ }$ , without incurring a grating lobe.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] This requires that the grating lobes be separated by at least $180^{\circ }$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] From the definition of $\psi$ , we see that maxima will occur whenever $2\pi n={\frac {2\pi }{\lambda }}d\times \left(\cos \theta -\cos \theta _{T}\right)$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The first grating lobe will occur at $|n|=1$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] For a beam steered to $\theta _{T}=180^{\circ }$ , we require the grating lobe to be no closer than $\theta =0^{\circ }$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Alternatively, one can think of a uniform linear array (ULA) as spatial sampling of a signal in the same sense as time sampling of a signal.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Grating lobes are identical to aliasing that occurs in time series analysis for an under-sampled signal.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Per Shannon's sampling theorem, the sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency of the desired signal in order to preclude spectral aliasing.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Because the beam pattern (or array factor) of a linear array is the Fourier transform of the element pattern, the sampling theorem directly applies, but in the spatial instead of spectral domain.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) of a sampled signal is always periodic, producing "copies" of the spectrum at intervals of the sampling frequency.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] In the spatial domain, these copies are the grating lobes.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The analog of radian frequency in the time domain is wavenumber, $k={\frac {2\pi }{\lambda }}$ radians per meter, in the spatial domain.
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] Therefore the spatial sampling rate, in samples per meter, must be $\geq 2{\frac {samples}{cycle}}\times {\frac {k{\frac {radians}{meter}}}{2\pi {\frac {radians}{cycle}}}}$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/grating-lobe] The sampling interval, which is the inverse of the sampling rate, in meters per sample, must be $\leq {\frac {\lambda }{2}}$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In antenna theory, a **phased array** usually means an **electronically scanned array**, a computer-controlled array of antennas which creates a beam of radio waves that can be electronically steered to point in different directions without moving the antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In a phased array, the power from the transmitter is fed to the radiating elements through devices called *phase shifters*, controlled by a computer system, which can alter the phase or signal delay electronically, thus steering the beam of radio waves to a different direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Since the size of an antenna array must extend many wavelengths to achieve the high gain needed for narrow beamwidth, phased arrays are mainly practical at the high frequency end of the radio spectrum, in the UHF and microwave bands, in which the operating wavelengths are conveniently small.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased arrays were originally invented for use in military radar systems, to detect fast moving planes and missiles, but are now widely used and have spread to civilian applications such as 5G MIMO for cell phones.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phased array principle is also used in acoustics in such applications as phased array ultrasonics, and in optics.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The term "phased array" is also used to a lesser extent for unsteered array antennas in which the radiation pattern of the antenna array is fixed.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] For example, AM broadcast radio antennas consisting of multiple mast radiators are also called "phased arrays".
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A phased array is an **electronically scanned array**, a computer-controlled array of antennas which creates a beam of radio waves that can be electronically steered to point in different directions without moving the antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The general theory of an electromagnetic phased array also finds applications in ultrasonic and medical imaging application (*phased array ultrasonics*) and in optics (*optical phased array*).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In a simple array antenna, the radio frequency current from the transmitter is fed to multiple individual antenna elements with the proper phase relationship so that the radio waves from the separate elements combine (superpose) to form beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This can be configured to increase power radiated in desired directions and suppress radiation in undesired directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In a phased array, the power from the transmitter is fed to the radiating elements through devices called *phase shifters*, controlled by a computer system.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The computer can alter the phase or signal delay of each antenna element electronically, resulting in a beam of radio waves that can be dynamically "steered" to propagate in arbitrary directions.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased arrays were originally conceived for use in military radar systems, to steer a beam of radio waves quickly across the sky to detect planes and missiles.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These systems are now widely used and have spread to civilian applications such as 5G MIMO for cell phones.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phased array principle is also used in acoustics, and phased arrays of acoustic transducers are used in medical ultrasound imaging scanners (phased array ultrasonics), oil and gas prospecting (reflection seismology), and military sonar systems.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The term "phased array" is also used to a lesser extent for non steerable array antennas in which the phase of the feed power and thus the radiation pattern of the antenna array is fixed.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] For example, AM broadcast radio antennas consisting of multiple mast radiators fed so as to create a specific radiation pattern are also called "phased arrays".
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] However, the four most common are the passive electronically scanned array (PESA), active electronically scanned array (AESA), hybrid beam forming phased array, and digital beam forming (DBF) array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A *passive phased array* or *passive electronically scanned array* (PESA) is a phased array in which the antenna elements are connected to a single transmitter and/or receiver, as shown in the first animation at top.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] PESAs are the most common type of phased array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Generally speaking, a PESA uses one receiver/exciter for the entire array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] An *active phased array* or *active electronically scanned array* (AESA) is a phased array in which each antenna element has an analog transmitter/receiver (T/R) module which creates the phase shifting required to electronically steer the antenna beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Active arrays are a more advanced, second-generation phased-array technology that are used in military applications; unlike PESAs they can radiate several beams of radio waves at multiple frequencies in different directions simultaneously.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] However, the number of simultaneous beams is limited by practical reasons of electronic packaging of the beam formers to approximately three simultaneous beams for an AESA.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Each beam former has a receiver/exciter connected to it.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A *digital beam forming (DBF) phased array* has a digital receiver/exciter at each element in the array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The signal at each element is digitized by the receiver/exciter.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This means that antenna beams can be formed digitally in a field programmable gate array (FPGA) or the array computer.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This approach allows for multiple simultaneous antenna beams to be formed.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A *hybrid beam forming phased array* can be thought of as a combination of an AESA and a digital beam forming phased array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It uses subarrays that are active phased arrays (for instance, a subarray may be 64, 128 or 256 elements and the number of elements depends upon system requirements).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The subarrays are combined to form the full array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Each subarray has its own digital receiver/exciter.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This approach allows clusters of simultaneous beams to be created.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A *conformal antenna* is a phased array in which the individual antennas, instead of being arranged in a flat plane, are mounted on a curved surface.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phase shifters compensate for the different path lengths of the waves due to the antenna elements' varying position on the surface, allowing the array to radiate a plane wave.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Conformal antennas are used in aircraft and missiles, to integrate the antenna into the curving surface of the aircraft to reduce aerodynamic drag.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] There are two main types of beamformers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These are time domain beamformers and frequency domain beamformers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] From a theoretical point of view, both are in principle the same operation, with just a Fourier transform allowing conversion from one to the other type.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A graduated attenuation window is sometimes applied across the face of the array to improve side-lobe suppression performance, in addition to the phase shift.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Time domain beamformer works by introducing time delays.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The basic operation is called "delay and sum".
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It delays the incoming signal from each array element by a certain amount of time, and then adds them together.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A Butler matrix allows several beams to be formed simultaneously, or one beam to be scanned through an arc.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The most common kind of time domain beam former is serpentine waveguide.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Active phased array designs use individual delay lines that are switched on and off.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Yttrium iron garnet phase shifters vary the phase delay using the strength of a magnetic field.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] There are two different types of frequency domain beamformers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The first type separates the different frequency components that are present in the received signal into multiple frequency bins (using either a Discrete Fourier transform (DFT) or a filterbank).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] When different delay and sum beamformers are applied to each frequency bin, the result is that the main lobe simultaneously points in multiple different directions at each of the different frequencies.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This can be an advantage for communication links, and is used with the SPS-48 radar.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The other type of frequency domain beamformer makes use of Spatial Frequency.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Discrete samples are taken from each of the individual array elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The DFT introduces multiple different discrete phase shifts during processing.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The outputs of the DFT are individual channels that correspond with evenly spaced beams formed simultaneously.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A 1-dimensional DFT produces a fan of different beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A 2-dimensional DFT produces beams with a pineapple configuration.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These techniques are used to create two kinds of phased array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] There are two further sub-categories that modify the kind of dynamic array or fixed array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Each array element incorporates an adjustable phase shifter.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These are collectively used to move the beam with respect to the array face.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Dynamic phased arrays require no physical movement to aim the beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This can produce antenna motion fast enough to use a small pencil beam to simultaneously track multiple targets while searching for new targets using just one radar set, a capability known as *track while search*.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] As an example, an antenna with a 2-degree beam with a pulse rate of 1 kHz will require approximately 8 seconds to cover an entire hemisphere consisting of 8,000 pointing positions.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This configuration provides 12 opportunities to detect a 1,000 m/s (2,200 mph; 3,600 km/h) vehicle over a range of 100 km (62 mi), which is suitable for military applications.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The position of mechanically steered antennas can be predicted, which can be used to create electronic countermeasures that interfere with radar operation.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The flexibility resulting from phased array operation allows beams to be aimed at random locations, which eliminates this vulnerability.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This is also desirable for military applications.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Fixed phased array antennas are typically used to create an antenna with a more desirable form factor than the conventional parabolic reflector or cassegrain reflector.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Fixed phased arrays incorporate fixed phase shifters.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] For example, most commercial FM Radio and TV antenna towers use a collinear antenna array, which is a fixed phased array of dipole elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In radar applications, this kind of phased array is physically moved during the track and scan process.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The SPS-48 radar uses multiple transmit frequencies with a serpentine delay line along the left side of the array to produce vertical fan of stacked beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Each frequency experiences a different phase shift as it propagates down the serpentine delay line, which forms different beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A filter bank is used to split apart the individual receive beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Semi-active radar homing uses monopulse radar that relies on a fixed phased array to produce multiple adjacent beams that measure angle errors.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This form factor is suitable for gimbal mounting in missile seekers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Active electronically-scanned arrays (AESA) elements incorporate transmit amplification with phase shift in each antenna element (or group of elements).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Each element also includes receive pre-amplification.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phase shifter setting is the same for transmit and receive.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Active phased arrays do not require phase reset after the end of the transmit pulse, which is compatible with Doppler radar and pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Passive phased arrays typically use large amplifiers that produce all of the microwave transmit signal for the antenna.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phase shifters typically consist of waveguide elements controlled by magnetic field, voltage gradient, or equivalent technology.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phase shift process used with passive phased arrays typically puts the receive beam and transmit beam into diagonally opposite quadrants.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The sign of the phase shift must be inverted after the transmit pulse is finished and before the receive period begins to place the receive beam into the same location as the transmit beam.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] That requires a phase impulse that degrades sub-clutter visibility performance on Doppler radar and Pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] As an example, Yttrium iron garnet phase shifters must be changed after transmit pulse quench and before receiver processing starts to align transmit and receive beams.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] That impulse introduces FM noise that degrades clutter performance.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Passive phased array design is used in the AEGIS Combat System for direction-of-arrival estimation.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] ballistic missile detection radar in Alaska.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Completed in 1979, it was one of the first active phased arrays.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Closeup of some of the 2677 crossed dipole antenna elements that make up the plane array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This antenna produced a narrow "pencil" beam only 2.2° wide.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased array transmission was originally shown in 1905 by Nobel laureate Karl Ferdinand Braun who demonstrated enhanced transmission of radio waves in one direction.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] During World War II, Nobel laureate Luis Alvarez used phased array transmission in a rapidly steerable radar system for "ground-controlled approach", a system to aid in the landing of aircraft.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] At the same time, the German GEMA company (German for *Gesellschaft für elektroakustische und mechanische Apparate*) built the Mammut 1.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It was later adapted for radio astronomy leading to Nobel Prizes for Physics for Antony Hewish and Martin Ryle after several large phased arrays were developed at the University of Cambridge Interplanetary Scintillation Array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This design is also used for radar, and is generalized in interferometric radio antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In 1966, most phased-array radars use ferrite phase shifters or traveling-wave tubes to dynamically adjust the phase.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The AN/SPS-33 -- installed on the nuclear-powered ships Long Beach and Enterprise around 1961 -- was claimed to be the only operational 3-D phased array in the world in 1966.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The AN/SPG-59 was designed to generate multiple tracking beams from the transmitting array and simultaneously program independent receiving arrays.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The first civilian 3D phased array was built in 1960 at the National Aviation Facilities Experimental Center; but was abandoned in 1961.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In 2004, Caltech researchers demonstrated the first integrated silicon-based phased array receiver at 24 GHz with 8 elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This was followed by their demonstration of a CMOS 24 GHz phased array transmitter in 2005 and a fully integrated 77 GHz phased array transceiver with integrated antennas in 2006 by the Caltech team.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In 2007, DARPA researchers announced a 16-element phased-array radar antenna which was also integrated with all the necessary circuits on a single silicon chip and operated at 30–50 GHz.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The relative amplitudes of—and constructive and destructive interference effects among—the signals radiated by the individual antennas determine the effective radiation pattern of the array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A phased array may be used to point a fixed radiation pattern, or to scan rapidly in azimuth or elevation.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Simultaneous electrical scanning in both azimuth and elevation was first demonstrated in a phased array antenna at Hughes Aircraft Company, California in 1957.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The total directivity of a phased array will be a result of the gain of the individual array elements, and the directivity due their positioning in an array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This latter component is closely tied to, but not equal to, the array factor.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Here, $\theta$ and $\phi$ are the directions which we are taking the array factor in, in the coordinate frame depicted to the right.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The factors $\beta _{x}$ and $\beta _{y}$ are the *progressive phase shift* that is used to steer the beam electronically.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The factors $I_{n1}$ and $I_{m1}$ are the excitation coefficients of the individual elements.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In all above equations, the value k describes the wavenumber of the frequency used in transmission.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These equations can be solved to predict the nulls, main lobe, and grating lobes of the array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It is common in engineering to provide phased array $AF$ values in decibels through $AF_{dB}=10\log _{10}AF$ .
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Recalling the complex exponential in the array factor equation above, often, what is *really* meant by array factor is the magnitude of the summed phasor produced at the end of array factor calculation.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This represents a coordinate frame whose $\mathbf {x}$ axis is aligned with the array $\mathbf {z}$ axis, and whose $\mathbf {y}$ axis is aligned with the array $\mathbf {x}$ axis.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] These values have been clipped to have a minimum $AF$ of -50 dB, however, in reality, null points in the array factor pattern will have values significantly smaller than this.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased arrays were invented for radar tracking of ballistic missiles, and because of their fast tracking abilities phased array radars are widely used in military applications.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] For example, because of the rapidity with which the beam can be steered, phased array radars allow a warship to use one radar system for surface detection and tracking (finding ships), air detection and tracking (finding aircraft and missiles) and missile uplink capabilities.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Before using these systems, each surface-to-air missile in flight required a dedicated fire-control radar, which meant that radar-guided weapons could only engage a small number of simultaneous targets.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased array systems can be used to control missiles during the mid-course phase of the missile's flight.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] During the terminal portion of the flight, continuous-wave fire control directors provide the final guidance to the target.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Because the antenna pattern is electronically steered, phased array systems can direct radar beams fast enough to maintain a fire control quality track on many targets simultaneously while also controlling several in-flight missiles.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The German Navy and the Royal Dutch Navy have developed the Active Phased Array Radar System (APAR).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The MIM-104 Patriot and other ground-based antiaircraft systems use phased array radar for similar benefits.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased arrays are used in naval sonar, in active (transmit and receive) and passive (receive only) and hull-mounted and towed array sonar.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] One of first acoustic phased arrays was the German Gruppenhorchgerät device.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In acoustics, microphone arrays and line arrays of loudspeakers are also used.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The *MESSENGER* spacecraft was a space probe mission to the planet Mercury (2011–2015).
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This was the first deep-space mission to use a phased-array antenna for communications.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The radiating elements are circularly-polarized, slotted waveguides.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The antenna, which uses the X band, used 26 radiative elements and can gracefully degrade.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The National Severe Storms Laboratory has been using a SPY-1A phased array antenna, provided by the US Navy, for weather research at its Norman, Oklahoma facility since April 23, 2003.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It is hoped that research will lead to a better understanding of thunderstorms and tornadoes, eventually leading to increased warning times and enhanced prediction of tornadoes.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The project includes research and development, future technology transfer and potential deployment of the system throughout the United States.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It is expected to take 10 to 15 years to complete and initial construction was approximately $25 million.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A team from Japan's RIKEN Advanced Institute for Computational Science (AICS) has begun experimental work on using phased-array radar with a new algorithm for instant weather forecasts.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Within the visible and infrared spectrum of electromagnetic waves it is possible to construct optical phased arrays (OPAs) which allow for dynamic beam forming and beam steering without mechanically moving parts.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] They are used in wavelength multiplexers and filters for telecommunication purposes, as well as in Lidar, Free-space optical communication, and holography.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] OPAs were also shown to enable lensless projectors, lensless cameras, and chip-scale optical tweezers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Due to the short wavelengths OPAs are typically realised in nanofabricated photonic integrated circuit platforms utilising materials such as silicon on insulator, germanium on silicon, silicon nitride or polymers.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Synthetic array heterodyne detection is an efficient method for multiplexing an entire phased array onto a single element photodetector.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Starlink is a low Earth orbit satellite constellation that is available in over a hundred countries.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] It provides broadband internet connectivity to consumers; the user terminals of the system use phased array antennas.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] By 2014, phased array antennas were integrated into RFID systems to increase the area of coverage of a single system by 100% to 76,200 m2 (820,000 sq ft) while still using traditional passive UHF tags.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A phased array of acoustic transducers, denominated airborne ultrasound tactile display (AUTD), was developed in 2008 at the University of Tokyo's Shinoda Lab to induce tactile feedback.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] This system was demonstrated to enable a user to interactively manipulate virtual holographic objects.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased Array Feeds (PAF) have recently been used at the focus of radio telescopes to provide many beams, giving the radio telescope a very wide field of view.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Three examples are the ASKAP telescope in Australia, the Apertif upgrade to the Westerbork Synthesis Radio Telescope in the Netherlands, and the Florida Space Institute in the United States .
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] In broadcast engineering, the term 'phased array' has a meaning different from its normal meaning, it means an ordinary array antenna, an array of multiple mast radiators designed to radiate a directional radiation pattern, as opposed to a single mast which radiates an omnidirectional pattern.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Broadcast phased arrays have fixed radiation patterns and are not 'steered' during operation as are other phased arrays.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Phased arrays are used by many AM broadcast radio stations to enhance signal strength and therefore coverage in the city of license, while minimizing interference to other areas.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] For shortwave broadcasts many stations use arrays of horizontal dipoles.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] A common arrangement uses 16 dipoles in a 4×4 array.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] Usually this is in front of a wire grid reflector.
[src:antenna-arrays/phased-array] The phasing is often switchable to allow beam steering in azimuth and sometimes elevation.
